## 10. CONTENT PRUNING & CONSOLIDATION

### The Quality Over Quantity Imperative

Content pruning—strategically removing, updating, or consolidating underperforming content—improves overall site authority and crawl efficiency.

**Why Prune:**

1. **Improved crawl budget allocation**: Search engines focus on quality pages
2. **Consolidated link equity**: Backlinks flow to fewer, stronger pages
3. **Eliminated keyword cannibalization**: One page ranks instead of multiple competing
4. **Better user experience**: Clear, comprehensive resources vs scattered information
5. **Stronger topical authority signals**: Depth over breadth
6. **Reduced maintenance burden**: Fewer pages to keep updated

### Content Audit: Identify Pruning Candidates

**Signals Content Needs Attention:**

**1. Zero or Minimal Traffic**
- No organic visits in past 6-12 months
- Fewer than 10 impressions per month in Search Console
- No ranking keywords (position 50+)

**2. Declining Performance**
- Traffic dropping consistently over 3-6 months
- Rankings falling from page 1-2 to page 3+
- Increasing bounce rate over time

**3. Thin Content**
- Under 300 words with no substantial value
- Generic content without unique insights
- Minimal text, no multimedia, poor formatting

**4. Outdated Information**
- Statistics from 3+ years ago
- Deprecated advice or techniques
- References to discontinued products/services
- Broken external links throughout

**5. Duplicate Content**
- Multiple pages targeting same keyword
- Similar content across different URLs
- Keyword cannibalization (competing with self in SERPs)

**6. Technical Issues**
- Slow page speed hurting site-wide metrics
- Mobile usability problems
- Broken functionality (forms, calculators, etc.)

### The Three-Way Decision Framework

For each piece of underperforming content, choose one action:

**1. Update / Refresh**

**When to Update:**
- Topic still relevant to business and audience
- Page has existing backlinks or some traffic
- Content can be saved with comprehensive refresh
- Ranking in positions 4-20 (improvement potential)

**How to Update:**
- Add 500-1,000+ words of new content
- Update all statistics and data
- Add new sections addressing gaps vs competitors
- Improve formatting (headings, lists, tables)
- Add multimedia (images, videos, infographics)
- Update title, meta description with current keywords
- Fix broken links, add new internal/external links
- Optimize for featured snippets if applicable
- Change publication date to signal freshness

**2. Merge / Consolidate**

**When to Merge:**
- Multiple posts covering the same or very similar topics
- Keyword cannibalization detected
- Related content would be stronger combined
- One page has backlinks, another has better content

**How to Merge:**
- Choose the **strongest URL** (factors: backlinks, traffic, authority, age)
- Combine **best content from all versions** into comprehensive resource
- **Edit thoroughly** to maintain logical flow, remove redundancy
- **Implement 301 redirects** from removed URLs to chosen URL
- **Update all internal links** throughout site to point to consolidated page
- **Enhance with new sections** to exceed competitor comprehensiveness
- **Resubmit to Search Console** for re-indexing

**Example**: You have three blog posts:
- "Email Marketing Tips" (5 backlinks, 50 monthly visits)
- "Email Marketing Best Practices" (0 backlinks, 10 monthly visits)
- "How to Do Email Marketing" (2 backlinks, 30 monthly visits)

**Action**: Consolidate into "Email Marketing Tips" URL, redirect others, create comprehensive 3,000-word guide.

**3. Delete / Remove**

**When to Delete:**
- Content no longer relevant to business
- Extremely thin with no salvageable value
- Duplicate of existing better content (with redirect)
- Outdated beyond repair (old events, discontinued products)
- Never generated meaningful traffic or engagement

**How to Delete:**
- **If no external backlinks**: 410 (Gone) status code acceptable
- **If has backlinks**: 301 redirect to relevant page (not homepage)
- **If no relevant redirect target**: 301 to parent category or related topic
- **Update internal links**: Remove or redirect to alternative page
- **Remove from sitemap**: Prevent continued crawl attempts
- **Monitor in Search Console**: Ensure proper handling

**Important**: Never delete content with substantial backlinks without proper 301 redirects—you'll lose valuable link equity.

### Content Pruning Process

**Step-by-Step Execution:**

**1. Export Full Content Inventory**
- Use Screaming Frog or similar to crawl entire site
- Export Google Analytics data (traffic, bounce rate, conversions)
- Export Search Console data (impressions, clicks, positions)
- Combine datasets for comprehensive view

**2. Segment Content by Performance**
- **Keep & optimize**: Top 20% performers, recent content, strategic pages
- **Update immediately**: Positions 4-20, declining traffic, outdated content
- **Consolidate**: Keyword cannibalization clusters, overlapping topics
- **Delete**: Zero traffic/impressions, completely outdated, thin content

**3. Prioritize by Impact**
- **High priority**: Pages with some traffic but declining, cannibalization issues
- **Medium priority**: Very low traffic but good backlinks, completely outdated
- **Low priority**: Zero traffic, zero backlinks, outdated content

**4. Execute Systematically**
- Work through high-priority list first
- Implement 301 redirects carefully (test each one)
- Track URLs in spreadsheet with actions taken
- Monitor in Search Console for issues

**5. Monitor Impact**
- Track overall organic traffic trends
- Monitor rankings for consolidated pages
- Check for redirect errors in Search Console
- Measure crawl efficiency improvements

**Expected Timeline:**
- Small sites (50-200 pages): 2-4 weeks
- Medium sites (200-1,000 pages): 1-3 months
- Large sites (1,000+ pages): 3-6 months (phased approach)

**ROI Expectations:**
- Consolidation typically shows ranking improvement within 4-8 weeks
- Overall site authority metrics improve within 2-3 months
- Crawl efficiency gains immediate
- Long-term: maintained pruned site requires less ongoing work

